- Bold the direct answer word or phrase at the start, e.g. <strong>Yes.</strong> or <strong>No.</strong>.
- Use natural variants; do not keyword-stuff.
- Use FAQs to resolve final objections before the closing recommendation. Answers should remove hesitation around fit, setup, durability, compatibility, and buyer risk.
- At least 3 FAQ questions must address practical buying objections, such as adhesive failure, clamp fit, power-strip weight, standing-desk movement, renter safety, or cable capacity.

SECTION 11: Final Thoughts
\x3C!-- wp:heading --\x3E<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>\x3C!-- /wp:heading --\x3E
- This must be the final substantive section before any schema/hidden technical markup.
- Write exactly two short paragraphs.
- Paragraph 1 summarizes the buyer decision and includes the natural target topic.
- Paragraph 2 names 2-3 strongest products using short product names and links them to Amazon with the same sponsored nofollow format.
- End with a clear buying direction, not a vague summary. The last sentence should tell the reader which type of buyer should click the strongest pick first.
- Do not just repeat the quick picks.

FINAL QA BEFORE OUTPUT
- Raw Gutenberg HTML only.
- Exactly one product shortcode.
- Exactly one table.
- No H1.
- No markdown syntax.
- No fake testing.
- No unsupported claims.
- If product review text is absent, do not mention reviews, owner feedback, missing reviews, or unavailable feedback.
- Must include Summary, Why These Picks Made the List, How to Choose, Which Should You Actually Buy?, FAQs, and Final Thoughts.
- Must not include a long Product Details section that repeats shortcode product cards.
- Must not include product-level Pros, Cons, or Key Specifications lists outside the ACMS shortcode.
- Must not include full-length Amazon product titles as headings.
- Must not contain the em dash character "—".
- No awkward phrase "right best".
- No forced irrelevant internal links.
- The article must make the buying decision easier than a generic roundup: clear winner by use case, honest objections, comparison logic, and final click direction.
`;

